%N A395522 Square table read by antidiagonals downwards: T(n,k) is the period of {F^(n)(x) mod k} for n >= 1, k >= 1, where F^(n) means the n-th iteration of the Fibonacci sequence (A000045).
%C A395522 Each column is periodic, because {F^(n) mod k} (a sequence of functions Z -> Z/kZ) is periodic (see A395523).
%C A395522 Obviously T(n,k) divides T(n-1,A001175(k)), but it can happen that these two are not equal: T(4,A001175(11)) = 120, but T(5,11) = 60.
%C A395522 Conjecture: each column is eventually constant. See the Math Stack Exchange link below for a more detailed introduction of the background of this conjecture. Note that, since T(n,k) can divide properly T(n-1,A001175(k)), this eventual period of {F^(n)(x) mod k} for sufficiently large n is not necessaily equal to A235249(k), the fixed point when A001175 is iterated with starting value k.
%H A395522 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395522/b395522.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..5050</a> (first 100 antidiagonals)
%H A395522 Math Stack Exchange, <a href="https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/5136002/do-the-periods-of-iterated-fibonacci-sequences-modulo-k-stabilize">Do the periods of iterated Fibonacci sequences modulo k stabilize?</a>.
